<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is GVWR and why does it matter for towing?", answer: "GVWR (Gross Vehicle Weight Rating) is the maximum total weight your vehicle can safely handle, including the vehicle itself, passengers, cargo, and tongue weight from a trailer. It is set by the manufacturer and found on the driver's door jamb sticker. Exceeding GVWR stresses the frame, suspension, brakes, and tires beyond their design limits, creating dangerous handling and stopping conditions." },
  { question: "How do I calculate my towing capacity?", answer: "Start with your vehicle's GVWR, subtract the curb weight (empty vehicle weight) to get maximum payload. Then subtract any passengers and cargo you are carrying. The remaining payload capacity determines your maximum towing, because the trailer's tongue weight counts as part of your payload. Divide remaining payload by the tongue weight percentage (typically 10-15%) to get maximum trailer weight." },
  { question: "What is tongue weight and how much should it be?", answer: "Tongue weight is the downward force the trailer hitch exerts on the tow vehicle. For conventional trailers, tongue weight should be 10-15% of the total trailer weight. For fifth-wheel trailers, it should be 15-25%. Too little tongue weight causes trailer sway, while too much overloads the rear axle and can lift the front wheels, reducing steering and braking effectiveness." },
  { question: "What is the difference between GVWR and GCWR?", answer: "GVWR is the maximum weight of the vehicle alone with all its contents. GCWR (Gross Combined Weight Rating) is the maximum weight of the vehicle plus the trailer combined. GCWR is always higher than GVWR. When towing, you must stay within both ratings. Your towing capacity is limited by whichever rating you reach first." },
  { question: "Can I tow more than my rated capacity?", answer: "No, you should never exceed your vehicle's rated towing capacity. The ratings account for frame strength, suspension, brakes, transmission cooling, engine power, and tire capacity. Exceeding these limits causes excessive wear, overheating, brake fade, suspension damage, and significantly increases the risk of accidents. Many states also have laws against overloaded vehicles, with fines and liability implications." }
]) %>

